    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> You'd need an enormous amount of power + luck in a significant large network.\n\nAn individual miner indeed needs luck to successfully mine a block.\nBut a malicious miner still spends nothing to attempt such spam attack: he does not need to broadcast such transactions to the network, and only include them in the block he's attempting to mine.\n\n> I don't want to compare us to any other blockchain tech, but don't all the chains \"suffer\" from this type of behaviour. Has it ever been a issue for them? I unfortunately don't know much about BTC mining for it to answer myself.\n\nWell, that's true, in any other blockchain technology miners can include useless transactions that can make everyone else waste bandwidth and transaction space, but my biggest concern here is that a rich malicious ethereum miner can make us waste storage space or force us to use enormous amounts of memory with very little effort and no cost in resources on his part (e.g. imagine such rich miner sending something like `[0x100000000]:1` or `[0x1000000000]:1` and knocking most other nodes offline).\n",
